{
  "text": "Toxoplasma gondii, an obligate intracellular parasite, can infect virtually all warm-blooded animals, including humans. Humans and animals become infected by eating undercooked or raw meat containing cysts, or by consuming food contaminated with sporulated oocysts [CITATION_1] . Understanding the prevalence of T. gondii infection in dogs is of economic and public health importance. Firstly, the infection is serious in young dogs, especially in those co-infected with canine distemper virus [CITATION_2] . Secondly, dogs are potentially involved in the mechanical transmission of T. gondii oocysts to humans, and shed parasite in their saliva [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Thirdly, in regions where dogs are used as food animals, T. gondii can be transmitted to humans by consumption of undercooked meat from infected dogs [CITATION_6] . Lastly, dogs are the most common pets in the world, and also reflect the extent of T. gondii infection in the domestic environment [CITATION_7] .",
